a Shrinking Equality Opportunity Structure -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFew moments in Canadian history are as intriguing as the political battle between Prime Minister Pierre Trudeau and the “Gang of Eight” provincial premiers who opposed his plans to “patriate” Canada’s constitution from Britain. This volume revisits these constitutional negotiations, including the personalities, visions, and political struggles that shaped the resulting constitutional agreement. Offering fresh perspectives on the politics of this key moment in Canadian history, it focuses on the players behind the patriation process, including First Nations and feminist activists, who helped shape Canada’s new constitution. Patriation and Its Consequences also explores the long shadow of patriation, including the alienation of Quebec, the character of Canadian federalism, Indigenous constitutionalism and Aboriginal treaty rights, and the struggle to ensure gender equality rights in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aConstitutional amendmentszCanada. 0aConstitutional historyzCanada. 0aFederal governmentzCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Constitutions.2bisacsh1 aAdams, Eric M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraul, Loren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrodie, Janine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBryden, P.E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDobrowolsky, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErola, Judith, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGagnon, Alain-G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relato